Q1. Signed char minimum value : -128

Explaination : The signed char occupies only one byte but can take both positive and negative values thus its range is -128 to 127. 
1 byte = 8 bits = 2^8 characters.
Thus half of these are positive while the rest are negative. Hence the negative characters are (2^8)/2 = 128, thereby making the minimum equal to -128.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Q2. Signed char maximum value : 127

Explaination :  The signed char occupies only one byte but can take both positive and negative values thus its range is -128 to 127. 
1 byte = 8 bits = 2^8 characters.
Thus half of these are positive while the rest are negative. Hence the positive characters are (2^8)/2 - 1 = 127, thereby making the maximum equal to 127. Zero is also a part of the positive characters as, thus the maximum is 127 and not 128.
    
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Unsigned char minimum : 0

Explaination: The unsigned char occupies only one byte but can take only positive values. Thus its range is from 0 to 255.
1 byte = 8 bits = 2^8 characters.
As the unsigned char takes only positive values the minimum automatically become 0.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Signed char maximum : 255

Explaination: The unsigned char occupies only one byte but can take only positive values. Thus its range is from 0 to 255.
1 byte = 8 bits = 2^8 characters.
As the unsigned char takes only positive values, the maximum value that it can take is (2^8) - 1 = 255 as zero is also included in those 256 values.

